From: AGX team
Subject: [PATCH] zero every journal block during mkfs, not just iblock 0

The original mkfs journal-init loop only writes to iblock 0
(the JBD superblock); every subsequent journal block is
allocated but not touched. lwext4's buffer cache then
returns whatever heap content was previously parked in the
backing page when those blocks are eventually read back —
including stale JBD2 magic from the iblock-0 write that
might have shared a cache slot.

For a freshly-mkfs'd filesystem the journal log SHOULD be
all zeros so journal replay starts in the canonical
"nothing to replay" state. Two consequences of the
not-zeroing today:

  1. The on-disk image is non-deterministic across two
     identical mkfs runs (the heap bytes in cache slots
     differ).
  2. Journal replay on a freshly-mkfs'd image may
     mistakenly interpret cache leftovers as real
     descriptor / commit / revoke blocks. Linux's e2fsck
     defenses against torn writes mostly catch this, but
     it's still a stale-data-on-disk smell.

Fix: zero the block before writing the JBD superblock for
iblock 0, and zero-then-commit every iblock > 0 too. Each
journal block becomes a deterministic all-zero buffer
(except for iblock 0's documented JBD superblock fields).
--- a/src/ext4_mkfs.c
+++ b/src/ext4_mkfs.c
@@ -665,16 +665,32 @@
 		if (ret != EOK)
 			goto Finish;

-		if (iblock != 0)
+		if (iblock != 0) {
+			/* AGX: zero every other journal block too —
+			 * otherwise the buffer cache leaks stale heap
+			 * content into the on-disk image. */
+			ret = ext4_block_get(fs->bdev, &blk, fblock);
+			if (ret != EOK)
+				goto Finish;
+			memset(blk.data, 0, info->block_size);
+			ext4_bcache_set_dirty(blk.buf);
+			ret = ext4_block_set(fs->bdev, &blk);
+			if (ret != EOK)
+				goto Finish;
 			continue;
+		}

 		ret = ext4_block_get(fs->bdev, &blk, fblock);
 		if (ret != EOK)
 			goto Finish;


+		/* AGX: zero the whole block before writing the
+		 * JBD superblock fields — sizeof(jbd_sb) is < the
+		 * 4 KiB block, and the tail must be deterministic
+		 * zeros, not whatever the buffer cache had. */
+		memset(blk.data, 0, info->block_size);
 		struct jbd_sb * jbd_sb = (struct jbd_sb * )blk.data;
-		memset(jbd_sb, 0, sizeof(struct jbd_sb));

 		jbd_sb->header.magic = to_be32(JBD_MAGIC_NUMBER);
 		jbd_sb->header.blocktype = to_be32(JBD_SUPERBLOCK_V2);
